The '''black-collared bulbul''' ('''''Neolestes torquatus'''''), or '''black-collared greenbul''', is a species of [[songbird]] in the [[bulbul]] family, Pycnonotidae. It is [[monotypic]] within the genus '''''Neolestes'''''.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=Dowsett |first=Robert J. |last2=Olson |first2=Storrs L. |last3=Roy |first3=Michael S. |last4=Dowsett-Lemaire |first4=Françoise |date=1999 |title=Systematic status of the Black-collared Bulbul Neolestes torquatus |url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1474-919X.1999.tb04259.x |journal=Ibis |language=en |volume=141 |issue=1 |pages=22–28 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1999.tb04259.x |issn=1474-919X|url-access=subscription }}</ref> For many years, some authorities considered the genus to belong to the [[bushshrike]] or [[shrike]] families due to shape and plumage similarities until a review of molecular genetic relationships in 1999 confirmed the behavioral and morphological affinities to Pycnonotidae.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zuccon|first=Dario|last2=Ericson|first2=Per G. P.|date=1 April 2010|title=The phylogenetic position of the Black-collared Bulbul Neolestes torquatus|journal=Ibis|language=en|volume=152|issue=2|pages=386–392|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.2009.00986.x|issn=1474-919X}}</ref>
The black-collared bulbul is found in equatorial Africa in its natural [[habitat]] of dry [[savanna]].

Originally misclassified due to its external similarity to bushshrikes (Malaconotidae) or true shrikes ([[Labiinae|Laniidae]]), molecular studies in the late 1990s confirmed its rightful place in the bulbul family (Pycnonotidae). This finding highlighted the importance of genetic data in [[ornithology]], as plumage and body shape alone can be misleading due to convergent evolution—when unrelated species evolve similar traits independently.<ref name=":0" />

The black-collared bulbul is [[Omnivore|omnivorous]], feeding primarily on insects, spiders, and other small invertebrates, but it also consumes fruits and berries when available. This flexible diet allows it to thrive in the seasonally arid savannas of central Africa. The species is found across parts of equatorial Africa, including countries such as Gabon, [[Republic of the Congo]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[Cameroon]], and [[Central African Republic]]. Its preferred habitat includes dry savannas, open woodland, and forest edges, where it forages among shrubs and low trees.

Being the sole member of the genus [[Neolestes]], the black-collared bulbul represents a distinct evolutionary lineage within the bulbul family. This monotypic status underscores its unique genetic and morphological characteristics, and may warrant special conservation focus as it embodies a separate branch of evolutionary history not shared with other bulbuls.

== Conservation status ==
According to the [[IUCN Red List]], the black-collared bulbul is currently listed as Least Concern due to its broad distribution and the lack of immediate threats to its habitat or population. However, ongoing threats such as habitat degradation, agricultural expansion, and deforestation could pose risks in the future if not properly monitored.

